 nothing more. Public figures do not have to take an oath of office swearing in the name of God, they may simply affirm with no mention whatsoever of God. They cannot be forced to do so either. The same applies in the courts. &#10;The Consitution Act has no reference to a Judeo-Christian God nor any other religion specific deity. All it states is the supremacy of God which was forced by Canadians from Nunavut and the Northwest Territories. Judeo-Christian is conspicuously absent. It simply does not exist. &#10;I am sorry, but in Canadian law, no reference giving deference to Christianity is legally possible nor is their any legislation to that effect. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="945" language="en" documentId="1517" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="FactNotFallacy2" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1517" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="247"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="248" end="519"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="520" end="800"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="801" end="945"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>